# Misata — Synthetic Data from Intent

**Generate realistic multi-table datasets from plain-English descriptions.**
No config files. No real data needed. Referential integrity guaranteed.

[![PyPI](https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/misata.svg)](https://pypi.org/project/misata/)
[![GitHub](https://img.shields.io/github/stars/rasinmuhammed/misata?style=social)](https://github.com/rasinmuhammed/misata)
[![Docs](https://img.shields.io/badge/docs-rasinmuhammed.github.io%2Fmisata-E89030)](https://rasinmuhammed.github.io/misata)

</div></cell id="title">
<cell id="install-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 0 · Install</cell id="install-header">
<cell id="install">!pip install misata -q</cell id="install">
<cell id="demo1-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 1 · One-liner demo

Describe a business in plain English. Get back a `dict` of DataFrames — one per table, FK integrity guaranteed.</cell id="demo1-header">
<cell id="demo1">import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

import misata

tables = misata.generate(
    "A SaaS company with 1000 users and monthly subscriptions.",
    seed=42,
)

for name, df in tables.items():
    print(f"── {name}  ({len(df):,} rows × {len(df.columns)} columns) ──")
    display(df.head(3))
    print()</cell id="demo1">
<cell id="fk-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 2 · Multi-table referential integrity

Three tables, two FK edges — no orphan rows, no manual wiring required.</cell id="fk-header">
<cell id="fk-demo">tables = misata.generate(
    "A fintech company with 2000 customers and banking transactions.",
    seed=42,
)

customers    = tables["customers"]
accounts     = tables["accounts"]
transactions = tables["transactions"]

print(f"  Customers:    {len(customers):>7,}")
print(f"  Accounts:     {len(accounts):>7,}")
print(f"  Transactions: {len(transactions):>7,}")
print()

orphan_accounts = (~accounts["customer_id"].isin(customers["customer_id"])).sum()
orphan_txns     = (~transactions["account_id"].isin(accounts["account_id"])).sum()

print(f"  Orphan accounts:     {orphan_accounts}  ✓")
print(f"  Orphan transactions: {orphan_txns}  ✓")</cell id="fk-demo">
<cell id="inspect-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 3 · Inspect the schema before generating

`misata.parse()` returns a `SchemaConfig` — review tables, columns, and relationships before committing to generation.</cell id="inspect-header">
<cell id="inspect">schema = misata.parse("A hospital with 500 patients and doctors.")
print(schema.summary())</cell id="inspect">
<cell id="curves-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 4 · Exact aggregate targets

"MRR rises from $50k in January to $200k in December with a dip in September" — Misata generates rows that actually sum to those targets.</cell id="curves-header">
<cell id="curves">import pandas as pd

schema = misata.parse(
    "A SaaS company with 1000 users. "
    "MRR rises from $50k in January to $200k in December with a dip in September.",
    rows=1000,
)

curve   = schema.outcome_curves[0]
targets = {pt["month"]: pt["target_value"] for pt in curve.curve_points}

tables  = misata.generate_from_schema(schema)
subs    = tables["subscriptions"].copy()
subs["month"] = pd.to_datetime(subs["start_date"]).dt.month
actuals = subs.groupby("month")["mrr"].sum()

MONTHS = ["Jan","Feb","Mar","Apr","May","Jun","Jul","Aug","Sep","Oct","Nov","Dec"]
print(f"  {'Month':<5}  {'Target':>12}  {'Actual':>12}  Match")
print(f"  {'─'*4}  {'─'*12}  {'─'*12}  {'─'*5}")
for m in range(1, 13):
    t = targets.get(m, 0)
    a = actuals.get(m, 0)
    ok = "✓" if abs(t - a) < 0.02 else f"Δ{abs(t-a):.2f}"
    print(f"  {MONTHS[m-1]:<5}  ${t:>11,.0f}  ${a:>11,.0f}  {ok}")</cell id="curves">
<cell id="curves-chart-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>### Revenue curve — visualised</cell id="curves-chart-header">
<cell id="curves-chart">import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as mticker

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 4))

months      = list(range(1, 13))
target_vals = [targets.get(m, 0) for m in months]
actual_vals = [actuals.get(m, 0) for m in months]

ax.fill_between(months, actual_vals, alpha=0.12, color="#E89030")
ax.plot(months, actual_vals, "o-", color="#E89030", linewidth=2.5, label="Generated MRR", zorder=3)
ax.plot(months, target_vals, "--", color="#e11d48", linewidth=1.5, label="Target", alpha=0.7)

ax.annotate(
    "Sep dip", xy=(9, actuals.get(9, 0)),
    xytext=(7.5, actuals.get(9, 0) * 0.75),
    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", color="gray"), fontsize=9, color="gray",
)

ax.set_xticks(months)
ax.set_xticklabels(MONTHS)
ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(mticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, _: f"${x/1000:.0f}k"))
ax.set_title("SaaS Monthly MRR — Generated vs Target", fontsize=13, fontweight="bold")
ax.legend()
ax.grid(axis="y", alpha=0.25)
ax.spines[["top", "right"]].set_visible(False)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()</cell id="curves-chart">
<cell id="healthcare-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 5 · Domain-realistic distributions

Healthcare blood types match real ABO/Rh frequencies. No configuration needed.</cell id="healthcare-header">
<cell id="healthcare">import numpy as np

tables   = misata.generate("A hospital with 500 patients and doctors.", seed=42)
patients = tables["patients"]

REAL     = {"O+": 38.0, "A+": 34.0, "B+": 9.0, "AB+": 3.0,
            "O-":  7.0, "A-":  6.0, "B-": 2.0, "AB-": 1.0}
bt_pct   = (patients["blood_type"].value_counts() / len(patients) * 100).to_dict()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 4))
x       = np.arange(len(REAL))
labels  = list(REAL.keys())

ax.bar(x - 0.2, [bt_pct.get(b, 0) for b in labels], 0.35,
       label="Generated", color="#E89030", alpha=0.85)
ax.bar(x + 0.2, list(REAL.values()), 0.35,
       label="Real-world", color="#2B4B82", alpha=0.85)

ax.set_xticks(x)
ax.set_xticklabels(labels)
ax.set_ylabel("%")
ax.set_title("Blood Type Distribution: Generated vs Real ABO/Rh Frequencies", fontweight="bold")
ax.legend()
ax.grid(axis="y", alpha=0.25)
ax.spines[["top", "right"]].set_visible(False)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

print(f"\nPatient age — mean: {patients['age'].mean():.1f}  std: {patients['age'].std():.1f}"
      "  (centred on chronic-care population)")</cell id="healthcare">
<cell id="fintech-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 6 · Fintech — calibrated fraud rate + FICO distribution</cell id="fintech-header">
<cell id="fintech">tables       = misata.generate("A fintech company with 2000 customers and banking transactions.", seed=42)
customers    = tables["customers"]
transactions = tables["transactions"]

fraud_rate = transactions["is_fraud"].mean() * 100
cs         = customers["credit_score"].dropna()

print(f"  Fraud rate:    {fraud_rate:.2f}%  (calibrated target: 2.00%)")
print(f"  Credit score — mean: {cs.mean():.0f}  std: {cs.std():.0f}  (real FICO: mean≈700, std≈75)")

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))

axes[0].hist(cs, bins=30, color="#E89030", alpha=0.85, edgecolor="white")
axes[0].axvline(cs.mean(), color="#e11d48", linestyle="--", label=f"Mean = {cs.mean():.0f}")
axes[0].set_title("Credit Score Distribution (FICO)", fontweight="bold")
axes[0].set_xlabel("Score")
axes[0].legend()
axes[0].grid(axis="y", alpha=0.25)
axes[0].spines[["top", "right"]].set_visible(False)

tc = transactions["transaction_type"].value_counts()
axes[1].barh(tc.index[::-1], tc.values[::-1], color="#2B4B82", alpha=0.85)
axes[1].set_title("Transaction Types (Zipf distribution)", fontweight="bold")
axes[1].set_xlabel("Count")
axes[1].grid(axis="x", alpha=0.25)
axes[1].spines[["top", "right"]].set_visible(False)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()</cell id="fintech">
<cell id="scale-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 7 · Scale — 1M rows in seconds</cell id="scale-header">
<cell id="scale">import time

t0     = time.perf_counter()
tables = misata.generate(
    "A large retail company with 50000 customers and 1 million orders.",
    rows=50_000,
    seed=42,
)
elapsed = time.perf_counter() - t0
total   = sum(len(df) for df in tables.values())

print(f"  Total rows: {total:,}  in {elapsed:.2f}s  →  {total/elapsed:,.0f} rows/s")
print(f"  (faster than reading the same data back from a CSV)")
print()
for name, df in tables.items():
    print(f"  {name:<16}  {len(df):>10,} rows  ×  {len(df.columns)} columns")</cell id="scale">
<cell id="locale-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 8 · Localisation — country-accurate data from your story

Drop a geographic signal in the story. Misata auto-detects the locale and generates the right names, salary distributions, national IDs, postcodes, and company suffixes.</cell id="locale-header">
<cell id="locale-demo">import misata

locales_to_try = [
    ("German SaaS company in Berlin with 200 enterprise customers", "de_DE"),
    ("Brazilian fintech with R$ payments and CPF verification, 200 users", "pt_BR"),
    ("Japanese ecommerce company in Tokyo with 200 customers", "ja_JP"),
]

for story, expected_locale in locales_to_try:
    detected = misata.detect_locale(story)
    pack     = misata.get_locale_pack(detected)
    tables   = misata.generate(story, rows=200, seed=42)

    # Show first 3 names from the primary table
    primary = list(tables.values())[0]
    name_cols = [c for c in primary.columns if "name" in c.lower()]
    sample_names = primary[name_cols[0]].head(3).tolist() if name_cols else []

    print(f"  Locale: {detected}  |  Currency: {pack.currency_symbol}  "
          f"|  Salary median: {pack.salary_median:,}  |  Sample names: {sample_names}")
    print()</cell id="locale-demo">
<cell id="locale-pack-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>### Inspect a locale pack directly</cell id="locale-pack-header">
<cell id="locale-pack">pack = misata.get_locale_pack("de_DE")

print(f"  salary_median:    {pack.salary_median:,}")
print(f"  currency_symbol:  {pack.currency_symbol}")
print(f"  top_cities:       {pack.top_cities[:5]}")
print(f"  company_suffixes: {pack.company_suffixes}")
print(f"  postcode_pattern: {pack.postcode_pattern}")
print(f"  national_id:      {pack.national_id_label}")</cell id="locale-pack">
<cell id="yaml-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 9 · YAML schema-as-code

Define your schema in a file, commit it to git, reproduce it anywhere.</cell id="yaml-header">
<cell id="yaml-demo">yaml_schema = """
name: demo-store
seed: 42

tables:
  users:
    rows: 500
    columns:
      user_id:   { type: int, unique: true }
      email:     { type: text, text_type: email }
      plan:      { type: categorical, choices: [free, pro, enterprise] }

  orders:
    rows: 2000
    columns:
      order_id:  { type: int, unique: true }
      user_id:   { type: foreign_key }
      amount:    { type: float, min: 10.0, max: 500.0 }
      cost:      { type: float, min: 5.0,  max: 200.0 }

relationships:
  - "users.user_id → orders.user_id"

constraints:
  - name: profit_margin
    table: orders
    type: inequality
    column_a: amount
    operator: ">"
    column_b: cost
"""

import tempfile, os
with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(suffix=".yaml", mode="w", delete=False) as f:
    f.write(yaml_schema)
    tmp_yaml = f.name

schema = misata.load_yaml_schema(tmp_yaml)
tables = misata.generate_from_schema(schema)
os.unlink(tmp_yaml)

orders = tables["orders"]
print(f"  Users:  {len(tables['users']):,}")
print(f"  Orders: {len(orders):,}")
print(f"  Constraint satisfied — all amount > cost: {(orders['amount'] > orders['cost']).all()}")
display(orders[["order_id","user_id","amount","cost"]].head(5))</cell id="yaml-demo">
<cell id="timeseries-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 10 · Time-series generation

Trend, seasonality, noise, and anomaly injection — from a plain-English description.</cell id="timeseries-header">
<cell id="timeseries-demo">ts = misata.generate_timeseries(
    "Daily active users over 1 year, growing 8% monthly "
    "with weekly seasonality and a viral spike",
    start_value=5_000,
    seed=42,
)

print(f"  Shape: {ts.shape}")
print(f"  Anomaly days: {ts['is_anomaly'].sum()}")
display(ts.head(5))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 4))
ax.fill_between(ts["date"], ts["daily_active_users"], alpha=0.12, color="#E89030")
ax.plot(ts["date"], ts["daily_active_users"], color="#E89030", linewidth=1.5, label="DAU")
ax.plot(ts["date"], ts["trend"], "--", color="#2B4B82", linewidth=1.2, alpha=0.7, label="Trend")

anomaly_days = ts[ts["is_anomaly"]]
ax.scatter(anomaly_days["date"], anomaly_days["daily_active_users"],
           color="#e11d48", zorder=5, s=60, label="Anomaly", marker="^")

ax.set_title("Daily Active Users — Trend + Weekly Seasonality + Viral Spike", fontweight="bold")
ax.set_xlabel("Date")
ax.set_ylabel("DAU")
ax.legend()
ax.grid(alpha=0.2)
ax.spines[["top", "right"]].set_visible(False)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()</cell id="timeseries-demo">
<cell id="validate-header"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## 11 · Validate a CSV

Profile any CSV for type correctness, null rates, uniqueness, and range stats.</cell id="validate-header">
<cell id="validate-demo">import tempfile, os

# Generate some data and save it as a CSV to validate
tables = misata.generate("A SaaS company with 500 users", seed=42)
with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(suffix=".csv", mode="w", delete=False) as f:
    tables["users"].to_csv(f, index=False)
    tmp_csv = f.name

report = misata.validate_csv(tmp_csv)
os.unlink(tmp_csv)

print(report)
print(f"  Score: {report.score}/100")
print(f"  Issues: {len(report.issues)}")</cell id="validate-demo">
